bout 1320–Deceased","1315–1363":"1315–1363","1312–Male":"1312–Deceased","1340–1399":"1340–1399","1320–Female":"1320–Deceased","Abt 1340":"about 1340","1315":"1315","1312":"1312","1399":"1399","Abt 1320":"about 1320","1320":"1320","1363":"1363","1340":"1340","Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Creedy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from North Creedy in Sandford or Lower Creedy in Upton Hellions (Devon).","2  Scottish Gaelic: from  <b>Mac Riada</b>,  see  McCready  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McCready","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Riada</b> ‘son of <i>Riada</i>’, an old personal name meaning ‘traveler, rider’. The surname was found in Galloway, Scotland, in 1684, but it seems likely (with the variant <b>McGready</b>) to have originated in Ireland."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Creedy was born about 1320."},"et":{"Abt 1320–":"umbes 1320–Surnud","1315–1363":"1315–1363","1312–Male":"1312–Surnud","1340–1399":"13